<meta name="socialpost1" content="Oil companies are blasting millions of gallons of toxic waste each year underground less than a half-mile from Enid, Oklahoma’s water wells. To protect their city, officials must appeal to the state agency that created the problem." />
<meta name="socialpost2" content="Oklahoma restricts the disposing of oil field waste within a half-mile of a public water well. Regulators have allowed companies to do so anyway. Now, to protect its drinking water, the city of Enid has to ask those same regulators for help." />
<meta name="socialpost3" content="Oklahoma approved oil field wastewater injection within a half-mile of a public water well, without making the company prove this would not pollute the city’s water. The site has repeatedly failed tests since, indicating a potential wastewater leak." />
<meta name="socialpost4" content="The Oklahoma agency responsible for ensuring that oil company operations do not pollute municipal groundwater has granted nearly 400 industry requests for injection rule waivers since 2022. Cities are powerless to pass their own rules." />
<meta name="socialpost5" content="In a rare example of pushback against a massive Oklahoma industry, Enid is asking state regulators for stronger protections against oil field waste potentially polluting its water supply. Already, five companies have formally opposed the request." />
